# Pandas 

### What is Pandas?

Pandas is an open-source Python library developed for data analysis and data manipulation. It provides fast, flexible, and easy-to-use data structures that help users work with structured data such as tables, spreadsheets, and databases.
Pandas is widely used in Data Science, Machine Learning, Artificial Intelligence, Data Analytics, Finance, Business Intelligence, and Research because it makes handling large datasets simple and efficient.
Pandas is built on top of the NumPy library, which makes numerical computations faster.

---

### Features of Pandas

- Easy to read and write data from CSV, Excel, JSON, SQL, etc.
- Provides powerful data analysis tools.
- Handles missing (null) values efficiently.
- Supports filtering, sorting, grouping, and merging data.
- Performs statistical operations easily.
- Integrates well with NumPy, Matplotlib, and Scikit-learn.
- Efficient for handling large datasets.

---

### Applications of Pandas

- Data Cleaning
- Data Analysis
- Data Manipulation
- Business Reports
- Financial Analysis
- Machine Learning Data Preparation
- Scientific Research
- Sales and Customer Data Analysis

---

### Basic Import

import pandas as pd

---

### Series

A Series is a one-dimensional labeled array capable of holding data of any type such as integers, strings, floats, or objects. Each value has an index.

### Syntax

import pandas as pd

s = pd.Series([10, 20, 30])
print(s)

### Output

0    10
1    20
2    30
dtype: int64

---

### DataFrame

A DataFrame is a two-dimensional data structure consisting of rows and columns. It is similar to an Excel spreadsheet or a SQL table. Different columns can contain different types of data.

### Example

import pandas as pd

data = {
    "Name": ["Ali", "Sara", "John"],
    "Age": [20, 21, 19]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)
print(df)

### Output

Name  Age
0   Ali   20
1  Sara   21
2  John   19

---

### Reading Files

Pandas can read data from different file formats.

- Read CSV File

df = pd.read_csv("data.csv")

Read Excel File

df = pd.read_excel("data.xlsx")

---

### Viewing Data

These functions help understand the dataset.

- First 5 Rows
df.head()

- Last 5 Rows
df.tail()

- Shape of Dataset
df.shape

- Column Names
df.columns

- Information about Dataset
df.info()

- Statistical Summary
df.describe()

---

### Selecting Data

- Select Single Column

df["Name"]

- Select Multiple Columns

df[["Name", "Age"]]

- Select Row

df.loc[0]

---

### Filtering Data

Filtering is used to display only the records that satisfy a condition.

df[df["Age"] > 20]

---

### Adding a New Column

New columns can be added easily.

df["Marks"] = [90, 85, 88]

---

### Updating Data

Values can be modified using loc.

df.loc[0, "Age"] = 22

---

### Deleting a Column

Columns can be removed using drop().

df.drop("Marks", axis=1, inplace=True)


---

### Handling Missing Values

Missing values are common in datasets. Pandas provides methods to detect and handle them.

- Check Missing Values

df.isnull()

- Remove Missing Values

df.dropna()

- Fill Missing Values

df.fillna(0)

---

### Sorting Data

Sorting arranges data in ascending or descending order.

df.sort_values("Age")

---

### GroupBy

The GroupBy function groups rows having the same value and performs operations like sum, average, count, etc.

df.groupby("Department")["Salary"].mean()

---

### Merge DataFrames

Merge combines two DataFrames using a common column.

pd.merge(df1, df2, on="ID")

---

### Saving Data

Save the modified DataFrame into a CSV file.

df.to_csv("output.csv", index=False)

---

### Advantages of Pandas

- Fast and efficient data processing.
- Easy handling of large datasets.
- Simplifies data cleaning.
- Supports powerful filtering and grouping.
- Easy integration with NumPy and Matplotlib.
- Reads and writes multiple file formats.
- Suitable for Data Science and Machine Learning.

---

### Limitations of Pandas

- Uses a large amount of memory for very large datasets.
- Slower than some specialized big-data frameworks for extremely large datasets.
- Mainly designed for structured/tabular data.

